The normal sublimation temperature is the temperature at which a solid substance is in equilibrium with its vapor at standard pressure (1 bar). The sublimation process for iodine is:
\begin{equation}
\ce{I_{2}(s) <=> I_{2}(g)}
\end{equation}
At equilibrium, the Gibbs free energy change for this process is zero, \(\Delta_{sub}G = 0\). The Gibbs free energy change is related to the enthalpy change (\(\Delta H\)) and entropy change (\(\Delta S\)) by the equation:
\begin{equation}
\Delta G = \Delta H - T\Delta S
\end{equation}
At the normal sublimation temperature, \(T_{sub}\), we have:
\begin{equation}
0 = \Delta_{sub}H - T_{sub}\Delta_{sub}S
\end{equation}
Rearranging this equation gives the formula for the sublimation temperature:
\begin{equation}
T_{sub} = \frac{\Delta_{sub}H}{\Delta_{sub}S}
\end{equation}
To find \(T_{sub}\), we first need to calculate the standard molar enthalpy of sublimation (\(\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus}\)) and the standard molar entropy of sublimation (\(\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus}\)) from the given data. We will assume that these values are approximately constant with temperature.

**Step 1: Calculate the standard molar enthalpy of sublimation (\(\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus}\))**
The enthalpy of sublimation is the difference between the standard molar enthalpy of formation of the product (gaseous iodine) and the reactant (solid iodine).
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus} = \Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) - \Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)})
\end{equation}
By definition, the standard enthalpy of formation of an element in its most stable state is zero. For iodine, the standard state is solid, so \(\Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)}) = 0\).
Given \(\Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) = 62.4\ \text{kJ}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\).
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus} = 62.4\ \text{kJ}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1} - 0 = 62.4\ \text{kJ}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}
\end{equation}
For consistency in units with entropy, we convert this value to Joules per mole:
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus} = 62.4 \times 1000\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1} = 62400\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}
\end{equation}

**Step 2: Calculate the standard molar entropy of sublimation (\(\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus}\))**
The entropy of sublimation is the difference between the standard molar entropy of the product (gaseous iodine) and the reactant (solid iodine).
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus} = S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) - S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)})
\end{equation}
Given \(S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) = 260.7\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}\) and \(S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)}) = 116.1\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}\).
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus} = 260.7\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1} - 116.1\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1} = 144.6\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}
\end{equation}

**Step 3: Calculate the normal sublimation temperature (\(T_{sub}\))**
Now we substitute the calculated values of \(\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus}\) and \(\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus}\) into the equation for \(T_{sub}\).
\begin{equation}
T_{sub} = \frac{\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus}}{\Delta_{sub}S_{m}^{\ominus}} = \frac{62400\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}}{144.6\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
T_{sub} = 431.535...\ \text{K}
\end{equation}
The given enthalpy value (\(62.4\ \text{kJ}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\)) has three significant figures, while the calculated entropy change (\(144.6\ \text{J}\cdot\text{mol}^{-1}\cdot\text{K}^{-1}\)) has four. The result of the division should be rounded to the lesser number of significant figures, which is three.
\begin{equation}
T_{sub} \approx 432\ \text{K}
\end{equation}

\boxed{432}\ \text{K}

